        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          The possession stats do not tell the real story of dominance. The way Opta (and now others) calculate possession is based on number of passes. This obviously causes a bias amongst those who play short passes between themselves regularly. In terms of time spent with the ball, we had what would amount to 75-80% possession for Spain but our midfielders spent a lot of time with the ball at their feet, not passing it 5 yards between each other, so it doesn't register the same way. This was the same with the Russia and Wales games. We've been the most dominant team in the completion (in real terms) but have yet again failed at converting chances. With teams who are content to defend for 90 minutes, we need to take the few genuine chances we get. Vardy and Sturridge in particular. They score those in the prem. Finishing 2nd isn't necessarily a bad thing providing we face Portugal in the last 16. They will actually try to attack. Worst case scenario would be Iceland. I dread that possibility!

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @Castle- I disagree regarding Wilshere although I'm sure people will say that's cos I'm a gooner. Jack has an excellent touch, good vision and can dictate play.... when he is in form. He's done that against Barcelona and Bayern before, albeit a while ago. You don't lose your ability- just fitness, form and confidence and all 3 are linked. He looks every bit the tin man pre-oiling. I would've started him in the game against Russia in the hope come the knockout stages, he would get some miles in his legs and build up his confidence. Our best midfield with everybody fit and 100% is Dier, Alli and Wilshere. 2 of those are out of form. Henderson on the other hand has no touch, no vision, is defensively poor and wastes 90% of dead ball opportunities he is given the responsibility of delivering. This is when he's playing "well". How he is in the squad ahead of Drinkwater, a clearly all-round better player, is beyond me.
